          "body": "The psalm's final verse is its most surprising and its most beautiful. After seven devastating acts of cosmic power, after the primordial flood and the eternal throne, the psalm ends in two short lines: the LORD gives strength to His people; the LORD blesses His people with peace. The word shalom carries all its Old Testament freight — not mere absence of conflict but the positive, comprehensive well-being of the covenant community living under God's protection. The structural signal is critical: oz (strength) has appeared in verse 1 as what must be ascribed TO YHWH; in verse 11 YHWH gives oz back to His people. The power the heavenly council was commanded to render upward is donated downward to those who worship Him. Swindoll captures the psalm's arc: 'The storm that terrifies the nations becomes the blessing that sustains Israel.' This is not sentimentality grafted onto a war-poem. It is the psalm's entire argument: the God whose voice is powerful enough to shatter Lebanon and shake Kadesh is powerful enough to keep His covenant people. Their shalom rests on His omnipotence, not on the favorable alignment of circumstances."
